content: I cant remember if I have posted in this group before but I wanted to get my story out there if any symptoms like mine develop in any of you, get to the doctor. I am also hoping someone has had the same issues I have that I can talk to.  For 20 years I have had out of control diabetes - no diet, no meds/insulin the drs tried me on, no amt of diabetes education, research, or nutrition classes have helped, exercising is not reducing my BS levels. It does not matter how strict my diet is I cant get under 200.  I am on an Insulin Pump and my BS is in the mid 300s all the time.  2.4 units of Novolog is being pumped into me per hour. I have to take 40 to 70 units of Novolog at meals to get my bs down.  I have seen tons of Internal Medicine doctors and on my third Endocrynologist.   I started developing diabetic neurapathy from the get go so they put me on Gabapenten and it has been working well so far.  But then 3 years ago, I developed Hypothyroid and all the symptoms of that was overlapping with the symptoms I get from high blood sugar making me severely fatigued all the time.  On top of all that my Vitamin D has not come up in 20 years leaving my back in severe pain off and on when levels are low.  I am on 2 50,000 units of supplements and sitting in the sun when I can - not helping.  Then in late May, while doing a Cat Scan on my ears, a mass next to my Pituitary Gland was found - a Pituitary Adenoma Tumor.  I went to Neurosurgeon and he wants to leave this large tumor there - a Macroadenoma because it is not affecting my Optic Nerves.  However all my research has led to this tumor is probably leaning on the Pit Gland and causing my diabetes issues,  my thyroid issues which they have to up my med twice since May and my Vitamin D issues.  My new Endo is doing further test to try to find proof why I need this surgery to get this Neurosurgeon to operate. My insurance will only allow me one more opinion.  They sent me to a military Neurosurgeon who is using all these scare tactics on me. I know the risk and I know the surgery will be dangerous. I just know these issues are being caused by the tumor and not anything I am doing wrong. I have tried everything under the sun to get my diabetes controlled and nothing I do or doctors do is working.

Hello all I have a question, this has been confusing me all weekend. According to the American diabetes association you have type 2 diabetes if A1c is 6.5 or higher or 126 mg/dl or higher. Yet this chart ( not from them but there is many online that agree) a 6.0 is the equivalent to 126. If that is correct then this info seems contradictory as according to A1c 6.0 is in the middle or pre diabetic range and 126 is type 2 . IF 126 and 6.0 are equivalent then according to A1c you are pre diabetic but according to mg/dl you have type 2, obviously this is contradictory . Please help 🤔

So I'm trying to calm it down and get to proper people, specialists groups, at the Mayo Clinic that can help me with resolving or not resolving the issues. Pain going down to the fingertips of my hands for which I am on medication but it is flared right now. I found that the only places that do this with groups of doctors is the Mayo Clinic and Johns Hopkins University. The group of doctors include neurosurgeons, orthopedic surgeons and muscular surgeons. I'm telling you this for somebody who may be going through the same issue. Is there anybody else out there that has found that's all they wanted do is diagnose and have physical therapy along with medications? And what do you do? To help keep your physical condition going and functioning?

Brand new here, used the search bar and did some reading.  I have what I believe to be statin-induced neuropathy.  I was on a low dose for 20 years.  I've had numbness in my second toes and moving to my third toes for a couple of years.  It's not getting any better.  I am sugar-free, grain-free, low carb, basically keto.  I also have Hashi's and hypothyroidism.  Anyone ever reverse this?  I'm 51...I'm super disappointed in myself for not learning about the ineffectiveness of statins in the first place, and also trusting the MD and never questioning if it was right for me or not.  I have NO PAIN...just this weird, crumpled up sock feeling under the bottoms of my toes.  It also seems like my second toes don't want to bend normally anymore, like on command, I can't get the right second toe to flex on the floor without me doing it manually.  It's like they're losing tone?  Anything help?  I take D, K2, Mag, ALA, B12, and the list goes on.  TIA!!

Here is one for 'the brains trust', as I've come to think of you all.. Having been diagnosed in April with idiopathic peripheral neuropathy, I have been in pain for much of the time. All quietened down last night. Still feels like I'm walking on eggshells and some toes are senstive  but I swear that the nerves are responsive. Being cynical by nature, and understanding that we fool ourselves, I went to see my podiatrist. After the normal barrage of tests, he confirmed that the nerves were still intact, and my neuropathy was 'positive', as opposed to the normal 'negative' type. Note: this is not a good/bad scenario. Being utterly confused as this stage, I asked him to explain - The nerves are ultra sensitive, and will over react. Tingling still occurs, due to the said sensitivity. Feels like I'm walking on eggshells, but it's false feedback. Big toes feel like the are inflamed, but they aren't. Still painful, but start to walk, as no damage is being done. Asked him about the prognosis; may go away in time, may stop tomorrow,  may persist, but the flare ups are rare and are less painful as time goes on. Oh, I did ask him if it could turn 'negative', he said not. Has anyone ever heard of this before?

I doubt I can keep this short but I'll try. I have osteoarthritis, DDD and familial stenosis at L4/L5/S1 area. I've also have SI issues that has caused pain in my right foot for years. My left leg has had issues with going numb or the feeling of pins and needles in the same area from my big toe up to my knee. I had one spine specialist tell me that she didn't understand why I would have this issue if the pain is usually located on my right side. I had a SI injection in the area that caused the most pain. I have had off and on  tailbone pain for awhile also but it was never consistent. After the injection, I started having more pain in the lower back/tailbone area. It seems since then (October 2019), problems have been ramping up with both my legs as a whole. I'm not blaming the injection BTW (unless I should?). Now the pain is so bad in that area I can't even stand for a few minutes before the burning/stabbing feeling brings my pain level up to an 8.  I've been experiencing neuropathy pain in my knees that have been getting worse over the past week. Since this has been happening it's now occurring in my whole lower leg and the bottoms of my feet. I have to keep my legs stretched out in order to get any relief. When I get up to start walking, my lower legs will feel like pins and needles. When I sit back down that's when I start to feel it in my feet. Before all this I could feel pulsing in my knees after walking. Now I feel pain 😑  Can this all be connected to my lower back issues? As the pain gets worse my mobility has gone down. I know this can make things worse in general. Thanks to anyone who took the time to read this :-)
